04656nam a22005655i 9780773566644DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735666447 a10.1515/97807735666442doi  a(DE-B1597)654768  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aT10.68bP69 1997eb 7aHEA0280002bisacsh04a363.1/001/41 aPowell, Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMad Cows and Mother's Milk :bThe Perils of Poor Risk Communication /cWilliam Leiss, Douglas Powell. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tWaiting for the Science -- tMad Cows or Crazy Communications? -- tA Diagnostic for Risk Communication Failures -- tDioxins, or Chemical Stigmata -- tHamburger Hell: Better Risk Communication for Better Health -- tSilicone Breasts: The Implant Risk Controversy -- tWaiting for the Regulators -- tLost in Regulatory Space: rbst -- tGene Escape,or the Pall of Silence over Plant Biotechnology Risk -- tMother's Milk: Communicating the Risks of PCBS in Canada and the Far North -- tTen Lessons -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first case study deals with the mad cow fiasco of 1996, one of the most expensive and tragic examples of poor risk management in the last twenty-five years. For ten years the British government failed to acknowledge the possibility of a link between mad cow disease and Creuzfeldt-Jakob disease, the human equivalent, until increased scientific evidence and public pressure forced them to take action, resulting in the slaughter of more than one million cattle. The second study looks at what is commonly known as hamburger disease, caused by a virulent form of the E. coli bacterium, which has struck thousands and killed over thirty people in the last few years. Despite its widespread effects, it is unclear whether scientific knowledge on preventing the disease is reaching the public. Other case studies include the use of a genetically engineered hormone to increase milk production in cows, health risks associated with silicone breast implants, public controversies surrounding dioxins and PCBs, and the introduction of agricultural biotechnology. These case studies show that institutions routinely fail to communicate the scientific basis of various high-profile risks. These failures to inform the public make it difficult for governments, industry, and society to manage risk controversies sensibly and often result in massive costs. With its detailed analyses of specific risk management controversies, Mad Cows and Mother's Milk will help us avoid future mistakes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHealth risk communication. 0aRisk communication. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Health Care Issues.2bisacsh1 aBarrett, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunk, Conrad G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffiths, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHrudey, Steve E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeiss, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMilly, Pascal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhitfield, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356664440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773